snippet.textDisplay:
Real people voted for Biden on Super Tuesday. How dare Sanders and Sanders Supporters dismiss anyone's opinion who voted for a different candidate. Seriously, how dare they? Biden won Super Tuesday because a lot of people are scared of Sanders' policies. Sanders had more money, more organization, far better press going into Super Tuesday (Remember: The press were saying Biden's campaign was dead!). It was a beautiful, truly democratic moment. A REAL MOVEMENT!!! It's just that it was a movement from the center, which doesn't happen every day.  

I don't think Sanders is the devil. I think he's a very decent, good man. And if he wins the nomination, it will be because more people in the party like his ideas than Biden's. I will support Sanders, even though he's not exactly in line with my way of thinking. I wish that Sanders supporters would get over the idea that it's their way or the highway. Sanders simply is a good man. But he's not for everyone. That's all. If Biden wins, it's not a conspiracy against your guy. Please keep that in mind.

When we're first starting out in life, we're all idealists, (and hard as it is to believe) even Republicans.

At various points in our journey, and due to our individual experiences, we grow, we change. But, it's not always for the better.

Senator Sanders embodies the hopes, the wishes, and the idealistic narrative we all once held for our families and our country.

At this point, I don't care any longer who the Democratic nominee is, I just want to see Trump replaced... and I think any Democrat can do that. And, although I've been a lifelong Democrat, I'd even settle for another Republican. It's that bad.

snippet.textDisplay:
It's not a conspiracy when people vote for someone who isn't Bernie. Real people cast votes in primaries--if you dismiss their actions as due to the evil influence of corporations in politics or the evil scheming of party leaders, you are dismissing those voters as tools or idiots. I can imagine Bernie winning. I agree that there's too much corporate and billionaire money in politics and it needs to be changed as soon as possible, no matter which Democrat wins. But it's also worth remembering that a majority of Democrats identify as moderate. A majority of Americans identify as moderate. You have to accept the legitimacy and the right to representation of people who do not agree with you.

Democrats who are terrified of Sanders need to accept that progressives are essential to the party and need to be flexible and ready to compromise so everyone gets representation.

Sanders supporters need to accept that moderates are a huge part of the Democratic party and that you need to be flexible and compromise because they too have a right to representation.

Without this tradition of tolerance and recognizing your political opposition as legitimate, Democracy doesn't work. And that has been on the wane for several decades, mostly due to Republicans. Now we see this attitude within the Democratic party.

I support the party leadership, like Nancy Pelosi, who had the wisdom to not try to impeach Trump the moment he was elected, to try to wait for a critical mass of support. Doing so too quickly would have strengthened him from the outset and delegitimized later criticism.

If you attack the entire party leadership as corrupt, you ignore the fact that a lot of Democrats don't entirely agree with your agenda.

The truth is, I support Democratic Socialism. I just think Bernie's uncompromising outsider attitude means he won't be able to build the necessary coalitions to get his plans through Congress.

When that happens, it's not only corporate influence, it's also the fact that they represent people who don't entirely agree with you, and (may be) because Bernie chooses a strategy of attacking them instead of flexibility to compromise.

Some Sanders supporters think a mass populist movement can pressure Congress to pass his agenda.

Trump supporters are not a majority, but they have been able to take over their party and turn it into the party of Trump. If their guy can't do what they want, they regard democratic institutions of checks and balances as illegitimate--something to be circumvented. Republicans have pursued tactics of forcing their agenda through against the will of the majority for decades now and democratic institutions are seriously weakened.

I don't want to see progressive populists adopt a similar thinking style and tactics.
